{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492424"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1059"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1059"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.03,0.06,0.29,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1059"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"3810"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14591"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent upper abdominal pain. She reports that over the past year she has been passing looser, smaller and more frequent stools 3-4 times a day, and has lost about 4 kg over the past two months due to decreased appetite. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She drinks about two glasses of wine on weekends and has a 20 pack year smoking history. She works as a farm manager on a sheep station.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild tenderness in the right upper quadrant without any palpable masses. An abdominal ultrasound is performed and a view of the right upper quadrant is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver cysts","Haemangiomas","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Metastatic deposits","Hydatid disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound image shows numerous hypoechoic (dark grey), solid-appearing lesions scattered diffusely throughout the liver. This appearance is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic deposits\u003C/strong\u003E, which is supported by the patient\u0027s clinical presentation of abdominal symptoms, changes in bowel habits, and unintentional weight loss, and her risk factors including age and smoking history. Given the patient\u0027s symptoms, colorectal cancer with liver metastases is a likely diagnosis. Primary tumors that commonly metastasize to the liver include colorectal, lung, and breast cancers. Further investigations such as CT chest/abdomen/pelvis and colonoscopy would be indicated to confirm the diagnosis and search for the primary tumor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cysts\u003C/strong\u003E have a very different sonographic appearance - they are typically anechoic (completely black) with smooth, well-defined margins and posterior acoustic enhancement (brightening deep to the cyst due to the fluid). They are also usually much larger than the lesions seen here. If there are other concerns, a hepatic CT or MRI could be done.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemangiomas\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common benign liver tumor. On ultrasound, they appear as well-circumscribed, hyperechoic (brighter than liver) lesions. They may have a hypoechoic rim or central scar. Haemangiomas are often solitary rather than multiple.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E (FNH) is a regenerative mass of normal hepatocytes that is usually asymptomatic and discovered incidentally. On ultrasound, FNH appears as a homogeneous, well-defined mass that is isoechoic or slightly hypoechoic to the surrounding liver parenchyma. A central scar may be visible spreading in a peripheral direction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus\u003C/em\u003E tapeworm which is ingested from contaminated food or handling dogs or dog faeces contaminated with the eggs. In Australia, most infections are spread between sheep and dogs, and the patient\u0027s occupation may put her at increased risk. However, hydatid cysts have a different appearance to the image shown in the case: they are typically anechoic (black), smooth, and round, and may have multiple small daughter cysts seen within the main cyst. They are also typically asymptomatic until they become very large or rupture. They most commonly involve the liver and lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple hypoechoic lesions in the liver on ultrasound are highly suggestive of metastatic disease, particularly in a patient with risk factors"],"references":["Mavilia MG, Pakala T, Molina M, Wu GY. Differentiating Cystic Liver Lesions: A Review of Imaging Modalities, Diagnosis and Management. Journal of  Clinical Translational Hepatology. 2018 Jun 28;6(2):208-216. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6018306/","Sutherland, T. Demystifying abdominal ultrasound. Australian Family Physician. 2009;38 (10). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/a551027c-ed92-49ca-964d-4e23b3705381/Demystifying-abdominal-ultrasound.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1059"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"244"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/244"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6532bcac-23ea-4a00-add3-1284125510e9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6532bcac-23ea-4a00-add3-1284125510e9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T20:16:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T20:18:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1059"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2